Sentencas: Bilayer electrolytes composed of an yttria stabilized zirconia (YSZ) layer (similar to 2 mu m) and a samaria doped ceria (SDC) layer (similar to 6 mu m) have been successfully fabricated by pulsed laser deposition (PLD) technique at 600 degrees C for thin film solid oxide fuel cells (SOFCs).
Titulo: Improved performance of solid oxide fuel cell with pulsed laser deposited thin film ceria-zirconia bilayer electrolytes on modified anode substrate

Sentencas: A NiO-YSZ (60:40 wt.% with 10 wt.% starch) anode supported YSZ/SDC bilayer electrolytes cell with Sm0.5Sr0.5CoO3-delta-Ce0.8Sm0.2O2-delta (SSC-SDC, 70:30 wt.%) cathode was tested, yielding open circuit voltage (OCV) value of 0.843 V and maximum power density of 0.87Wcm(-2)
Titulo: Improved performance of solid oxide fuel cell with pulsed laser deposited thin film ceria-zirconia bilayer electrolytes on modified anode substrate

Sentencas: at 700 degrees C. With a NiO-YSZ anode functional layer (50:50 wt.%) introduced into anode/electrolyte interface, significantly enhanced cell performance was achieved, i.e., the cell OCV of 0.959 V and 0.98V with maximum power density of 1.19Wcm(-2) and 1.08Wcm(-2) at 750 degrees C and 700 degrees C, respectively.
Titulo: Improved performance of solid oxide fuel cell with pulsed laser deposited thin film ceria-zirconia bilayer electrolytes on modified anode substrate

Sentencas: The electrical current leakage in the SDC single layer cell caused by the reduction of Ce4+ to Ce3+ in reducing environment has been eliminated by depositing the YSZ thin film as a blocking layer.
Titulo: Improved performance of solid oxide fuel cell with pulsed laser deposited thin film ceria-zirconia bilayer electrolytes on modified anode substrate

Sentencas: Characterization analysis of the cell showed that the bilayer electrolyte deposited by PLO technique have retained the chemical, mechanical and structural integrity of the cell.
Titulo: Improved performance of solid oxide fuel cell with pulsed laser deposited thin film ceria-zirconia bilayer electrolytes on modified anode substrate
